bug.summary: Tensor flow error when including tensorflow maven dependencies

comments.comment:
<denchmark-link:https://github.com/AmrRahmy>@AmrRahmy</denchmark-link> Thanks for reporting this issue. I noticed you are loading both libmxnet.so, libtorch.so and libtensorflow.so into the memory. Are you intend to use both of the engine? I suggest you only add one dependency if you don't need them, DJL will load all engines as long as they are in classpath:
It will use more memory to load both engine, the engine itself is not small most of DL engines use openmp, you might need to set KMP_DUPLICATE_LIB_OK=TRUE to avoid conflict and that may cause slightly performance impact.

I did notice the gpu memory usage increase when I added mxnet and tensor flow but it is only 1.8GB for inference.
I intend on using object detection, face detection, face recognition and pose estimation.
I noticed that pytorch only had the zoo model for resnet50. Mxnet had more options.
I am new to djl, if you can guide me to how to download and use the pretrained models, I would stick to one engine, like pytorch instead of using multiple engines. Right now I am using criteria to filter the artifact resnet50. I am also still looking for the filter to specify which gpu/cpu to use. There is a class Device, but not sure how/where to use it. <denchmark-link:#></denchmark-link>
On Thu, Jul 2, 2020, 7:53 PM Frank Liu ***@***.***> wrote: @AmrRahmy <https://github.com/AmrRahmy> Thanks for reporting this issue.
I noticed you are loading both libmxnet.so, libtorch.so and libtensorflow.so into the memory. Are you intend to use both of the engine?
I suggest you only add one dependency if you don't need them, DJL will load all engines as long as they are in classpath:
- It will use more memory to load both engine, the engine itself is not small - most of DL engines use openmp, you might need to set KMP_DUPLICATE_LIB_OK=TRUE to avoid conflict and that may cause slightly performance impact.

<denchmark-link:https://github.com/AmrRahmy>@AmrRahmy</denchmark-link> you can use the following commands to get the list of the models on the model zoo. <denchmark-code>./gradlew :examples:run -Dmain=ai.djl.examples.inference.ListModels -Dai.djl.default_engine=MXNet ./gradlew :examples:run -Dmain=ai.djl.examples.inference.ListModels -Dai.djl.default_engine=PyTorch ./gradlew :examples:run -Dmain=ai.djl.examples.inference.ListModels -Dai.djl.default_engine=TensorFlow </denchmark-code>
You can take a look at the <denchmark-link:https://github.com/awslabs/djl/blob/master/jupyter/object_detection_with_model_zoo.ipynb>how to easily load SSD model</denchmark-link> and <denchmark-link:https://github.com/awslabs/djl/blob/95bf02447bf5af2319266ee84ba931c75f90507a/examples/src/main/java/ai/djl/examples/inference/ObjectDetection.java#L55-L61>how to use criteria api</denchmark-link>

Not using gradle, I personally just want to use intellij idea projects with maven dependencies, but there is a list models function i used,
Map<Application, List<Artifact>> applicationListMap = ModelZoo.listModels(); for (Application application : applicationListMap.keySet()) { System.out.println(application.getPath()); List<Artifact> artifacts = applicationListMap.get(application); for (Artifact artifact : artifacts) { System.out.print("\t"); System.out.println(artifact.getName()); Map<String, String> properties = artifact.getProperties(); for (String property : properties.keySet()) { System.out.print("\t\t"); System.out.println(property + ": " + properties.get(property)); } } }
